{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17568313","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17568313"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T00:13:12+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T00:13:12+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"20013"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"20013","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/20013"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.04,0.13,0.1,0.71,0.02]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"12791"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"98593"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"12791","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/12791"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"20013"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"80989"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"11"},{"type":"tags","id":"13"},{"type":"tags","id":"14"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"30"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"160"},{"type":"tags","id":"1114"},{"type":"tags","id":"1590"},{"type":"tags","id":"2706"},{"type":"tags","id":"3773"},{"type":"tags","id":"4174"},{"type":"tags","id":"4897"},{"type":"tags","id":"4961"},{"type":"tags","id":"4966"},{"type":"tags","id":"4982"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11630"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"30177"},{"type":"contributions","id":"30178"},{"type":"contributions","id":"32567"},{"type":"contributions","id":"33806"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43730"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44320"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"98593","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/98593"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 62-year-old woman presents to the Emergency Department with three days of worsening shortness of breath and pleuritic chest pain. She tested positive for SARS-CoV-2 infection eight days ago. She has a history of emphysema and uses a fluticasone/vilanterol inhaler. On examination, she appears mildly distressed. Her pulse rate is 110/min, blood pressure 135/85 mmHg, respiratory rate 24/min, SpO2 91% on room air, and temperature 37.8\u00b0C. Her chest is clear to auscultation. Her jugular venous pulse is 2cm above the sternal angle. There is no leg swelling or tenderness.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EBlood tests reveal: C-reactive protein 85 mg/L (0-5), D-dimer 2.5 mg/L (0-0.5), haemoglobin 135 g/L (115-165), white cell count 8.5 x 10^9/L (4.0-11.0), platelets 450 x 10^9/L (150-400). Plain chest x-ray demonstrates bilateral patchy infiltrates consistent with viral pneumonitis.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate next investigation?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Serial troponin measurements","Echocardiogram","Ventilation-perfusion scan","Computed tomography pulmonary angiogram","Lower limb ultrasound"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThere could be a number of explanations for this patient\u0027s symptoms, and the most important to consider and exclude would be pulmonary embolism (PE). In the context of a recent COVID-19 infection, this diagnosis is a strong possibility among differentials including progressive COVID pneumonitis, bacterial superinfection, pericarditis, and complications of repeated coughing including musculoskeletal pain or pneumothorax from a popped emphysematous bulla. Various scoring systems exist to estimate pre-test probability for PE; tools like the Wells and PERC scores are in routine use and well-validated. In this case, the pleuritic chest pain, tachycardia, hypoxia and elevated D-dimer suggests a high pre-test probability for PE.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EWhile viral pneumonitis from COVID-19 could certainly cause an elevated D-dimer due to inflammation, it\u0027s crucial to recognize that COVID-19 significantly increases the risk of venous thromboembolism. The positive D-dimer in this context cannot be dismissed as merely due to the viral infection, especially given the clinical presentation. COVID-19 creates a hypercoagulable state through multiple mechanisms including endothelial injury, systemic inflammation, and immobility, making PE a serious consideration that requires definitive investigation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EComputed tomography pulmonary angiogram\u003C/strong\u003E is the most appropriate next investigation. The patient has significant risk factors (COVID-19 infection), concerning symptoms (pleuritic chest pain, tachypnoea, hypoxia), and an elevated D-dimer, warranting definitive imaging.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EVentilation-perfusion scanning\u003C/strong\u003E is an alternative to CTPA but is less suitable in COVID-19 patients due to the risk of aerosolisation during the ventilation phase and the likelihood of abnormal chest imaging affecting interpretation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EEchocardiogram\u003C/strong\u003E might be useful in this setting to identify indirect evidence of PE via features of right heart strain, or evaluate for less likely differentials such as pericarditis, but will neither confirm nor exclude PE.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESerial troponin measurements\u003C/strong\u003E may be elevated in both PE and COVID-19 but would not help establish the diagnosis of PE.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELower limb ultrasound\u003C/strong\u003E would only detect deep vein thrombosis and would not diagnose PE directly. While it might support the diagnosis if positive, a negative study would not exclude PE.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Traditional PE risk scores like Wells and PERC remain the standard approach to risk stratifying pulmonary embolism, even in COVID-19 patients.","CT pulmonary angiogram is the preferred imaging modality for suspected PE in COVID-19 patients due to potential difficulties with V/Q scanning.","While a normal D-dimer essentially excludes PE, an elevated value is highly non-specific with many causes including thromboembolism, inflammation, infection, malignancy, pregnancy, aging, strenuous physical activity, and more."],"references":["Franco-Moreno A, Palma-Huerta E, Fern\u00e1ndez-Vidal E, Madro\u00f1al-Cerezo E, Marco-Mart\u00ednez J, Romero-Pareja R, Izquierdo-Mart\u00ednez A, Carpintero-Garc\u00eda L, Ruiz-Giard\u00edn JM, Torres-Macho J, de Ancos-Aracil CL; CHEDDAR Research Group. External validation of the CHEDDAR score for suspected pulmonary embolism in patients with SARS-CoV-2 infection in an independent cohort. J Thromb Thrombolysis. 2024 Mar;57(3):352-357. doi: 10.1007/s11239-023-02918-3. Epub 2023 Dec 14. PMID: 38095742. https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/38095742/","Franco-Moreno A, Brown-Lavalle D, Rodr\u00edguez-Ram\u00edrez N, Mu\u00f1oz-Rold\u00e1n C, Rubio-Aguilera AI, Campos-Arenas M, Mu\u00f1oz-Rivas N, Moya-Mateo E, Ruiz-Giard\u00edn JM, Pardo-Guimer\u00e1 V, Ulla-Anes M, Pedrero-Tom\u00e9 R, Torres-Macho J, Bustamante-Fermosel A; Infanta Leonor Thrombosis Research Group. Clinical prediction model for pulmonary thrombosis diagnosis in hospitalized patients with SARS-CoV-2 infection. J Clin Transl Res. 2023 Feb 6;9(2):59-68. PMID: 37034002; PMCID: PMC10075091. https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC10075091/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"80989"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"20013"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"80989","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/80989"},